1 Loading & Describing Data

The beginning code chunk includes installing all packages needed for the analysis in one step, as well as any recoding done to ensure accurate results. The output below shows a summary of the variables after the data has been prepped, as well as a plot introducing the data. The only variable that was changed is Gender, as any customer who did not have a given value for gender was coded as âMissingâ. These values were kept in the data set for analysis.

library(pacman)
p_load(tidyverse, dplyr, plyr, DataExplorer, corrplot, knitr, ggplot2)
setwd("/Users/abbyfarrell/Documents/GitHub/BeachTanAnalysis")
df<-read.csv("BeachTan.csv", stringsAsFactors = TRUE)

#recode as factors
df$UIDStoreLocation <- as.factor(df$UIDStoreLocation)
df$MembershipType <- as.factor(df$MembershipType)
df$MembershipLevel <- as.factor(df$MembershipLevel)
levels(df$MembershipType) <-c('Non Membership', 'Monthly Membership', 'Annual Membership')
levels(df$MembershipLevel) <-c('Non Membership', 'Fast', 'Faster', 'Fastest', 'Instant')
df$Gender = fct_recode(df$Gender, 'Missing' = "", 'Missing' = "#NULL!")

str(df)

2 Plotting the Variables

We can see that we now have a relatively straight-forward data set with no missing values. This will allow us to examine any correlation between the given variables and upgrade revenue specifically. A correlation map of the numeric variables is shown below, as well as tabs for four different scatter plots and distribution graphs of the factor variables.

#Find correlation in variables
correlation <- unlist(lapply(df, is.numeric)) 
dfcorr<-df[,correlation]
M<-cor(dfcorr, use = "complete.obs")
corrplot(M, method='circle')

2.1 Plot

plot(df$UpgradeRevenue, df$MembershipType, main="Membership Type vs. Upgrade Rev", xlab = "Upgrade Revenue", ylab= "Membership Type", col="red")

plot(df$MembershipType)

2.2 Plot

plot(df$UpgradeRevenue, df$MembershipLevel, main="Membership Level vs. Upgrade Rev", xlab = "Upgrade Revenue", ylab= "Membership Level", col="blue")

plot(df$MembershipLevel)

2.3 Plot

plot(df$UpgradeRevenue, df$Gender, main="Gender vs. Upgrade Rev", xlab = "Upgrade Revenue", ylab= "Gender", col="green")

plot(df$Gender)

2.4 Plot

plot(df$UpgradeRevenue, df$UIDStoreLocation, main="Store Location vs. Upgrade Rev", xlab = "Upgrade Revenue", ylab= "Store Location", col="orange")

plot(df$UIDStoreLocation)

3 Analyzing Correlations

There are a couple observations we can make from the graphs above. First, looking at the correlation plot of numeric variables we can see that upgrade revenue has the strongest correlation with the number of UV Tans. The scatter plots showing the different factors against our target variable tells us which membership type and level contributed most to upgrade revenue. Now we can take a closer look at the variables that have the greatest correlation to upgrade revenue to confirm our findings, shown in the tabs below.

3.1 UV Tans

ggplot(data = df) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = UpgradeRevenue, y = UVTans))

3.2 Membership Level

ggplot(data = df, mapping = aes(x = UpgradeRevenue)) + 
  geom_freqpoly(mapping = aes(colour = MembershipLevel), binwidth = 500)

3.3 Membership Type

ggplot(data = df, mapping = aes(x = UpgradeRevenue)) + 
  geom_freqpoly(mapping = aes(colour = MembershipType), binwidth = 500)

4 Conclusion

From analyzing the graphs above, the conclusion that we can draw for the Beach Tan Marketing Team is that the customers with the highest number of UV Tans who have no membership yet should be targeted for upgrades. The lower the membership level and type, the more upgrade revenue the customer is likely to contribute to the company. This is shown through the correlation of these variables and the frequency at which they occur in Beach Tanâs customer base. If the existing customers of the company meet this criteria, they can be sent promotions and advertisements to push them towards upgrading within Beach Tan. This will increase revenue and customer loyalty for the company overall, as well as encourage more customers to upgrade within Beach Tan in the future.
